PY  - 1978
DA  - 1978/12/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(78)90009-0
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X78900090
AB  - We present sufficient conditions for taxable investors to be indifferent to dividends despite tax differentials in favor of capital gains (Strong Invariance Proposition). The conditions include two ‘seemingly unrelated’ provisions of the Internal Revenue Code: (1) the limitation of interest deductions to investment income received and (2) the tax-free accumulation of wealth at the before-tax interest rate on investments in life insurance. Although we use insurance for simplicity in the proof, many tax-equivalent investment vehicles now exist, notably pension funds. Our analysis suggests that the personal income tax is approaching a consumption tax with further drift likely.
